# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* included the names of over 20,000 native and adopted citizens of the United States, including living persons.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Also included were the names of several thousand citizens of all the other countries of North and South America.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The aim was to embrace all noteworthy persons of the New World.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The work also contained the names of nearly 1,000 people of foreign birth who were closely identified with American history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* was illustrated with about sixty full-page portraits supplemented by some 1,500 smaller vignette portraits accompanied by facsimile autographs, and also several hundred views of birthplaces, residences, monuments, and tombs famous in history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] None of the articles are signed either with names or with initials.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The clue to authorship is obtained, when obtained at all, through a list of contributors and their contributions arranged alphabetically as to contributors.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] One reviewer found this a rather inconvenient method, complaining that the finding of the author of a particular sketch often involved a voyage of discovery through the entire list.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] These lists are searched in vain, however, for the authors of many sketches, including the one of President Grover Cleveland.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The first discovery of these fictitious biographies was in 1919 by John Hendley Barnhart, when he identified and reprinted, with commentary, 14 biographical sketches of supposed European botanists who had come to the New World to study in Latin America.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] By 1939, 47 fictitious biographies had been discovered, though only the letters H and V had been systematically investigated.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The status of fictitious biographies in *Appletons' Cyclopædia* was also assessed by Margaret Castle Schindler of Goucher College in 1937.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] While three of the fictitious biographies (those of Joseph Dombey, Rafael Ferrer and Huet de Navarre) *were* about a real person, most of the details in these biographies were fictitious.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Joseph Cantillion identified the author of "phantom Jesuit" articles as William Christian Tenner: he identified 43 wholly fictitious subjects in this genre, as well as a mostly fictitious biography of Ferrer, and presented a list of 94 fictitious entries.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Dobson suggests Hermann Ritter, who appears as the source of "Articles on South and Central Americans" beginning with volume III, as another likely author of the fictitious articles.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Dobson notes that the first two volumes, where Juan G.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Puron appears in this role, are practically free of fictitious articles, although he identified an article on "Dávila, Nepomuceno" as suspicious, while "Chel-Ab-Ku-Kil", "Chignavitcelut" and "Oxiquieb Chiguaihue" are also listed as suspicious.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] In Dobson's 1993 study of Appleton's, he found four articles in the letter I to be fictitious.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Articles on "Ingulf von Köln, Rudolf" (listed as suspicious by Dobson) and "Zénon de Rouvroy, Charles-Albert" (sometimes mentioned as "de Rouvroy, Charles-Albert Zénon") were found by Williams in 2021 to be fictitious.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Contributors to *Appletons' Cyclopædia* were free to suggest new subjects and were paid according to the length of the article, with articles only being checked for form by the editorial staff.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] While conceding that *Appletons' Cyclopædia* was a "valuable and authoritative work", and that her results should not reflect on the many authentic articles, Schindler noted that articles on Latin American subjects should be used cautiously until verified against other sources.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The first edition of the *Cyclopædia* was published between 1887 and 1889 by D.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The general editors were James Grant Wilson and John Fiske; the managing editor from 1886 to 1888 was Rossiter Johnson.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] A seventh volume, containing an appendix and supplementary lists, and thematic indexes to the whole work, was issued in 1901.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* was republished, uncorrected, by the Gale Research Company in 1968.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] The journal was founded in 1978 by George Simson, a professor of literature at the University of Hawaii.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] Simson also founded the nonprofit Biographical Research Center (BRC) and the university's Center for Biographical Research (CBR).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] The journal is owned by the BRC and published by the University of Hawaii Press.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] For several years Professor Donald James Winslow of the University of Boston was the magazine's bibliographer.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] In 1994, the editorship passed to Craig Howes at the University of Hawaii, who gradually expanded the content and instigated a redesign in 1999.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography-journal] The journal's first electronic edition appeared in 2000 on Project MUSE.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] A **biography**, or simply **bio**, is a detailed description or account of a person's life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] It involves more than just basic facts like education, work, relationships, and death; it portrays a person's experience of these life events.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Unlike a profile or curriculum vitae (résumé), a biography presents a subject's life story, highlighting various aspects of their life, including intimate details of experience, and may include an analysis of the subject's personality.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biographical works are usually non-fiction, but fiction can also be used to portray a person's life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] One in-depth form of biographical coverage is called legacy writing.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Works in diverse media, from literature to film, form the genre known as biography.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] An **authorized biography** is written with the permission, cooperation, and at times, participation of a subject or a subject's heirs.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] An unauthorized biography is one written without such permission or participation.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] An autobiography is written by the person themselves, sometimes with the assistance of a collaborator or ghostwriter.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] At first, biographical writings were regarded merely as a subsection of history with a focus on a particular individual of historical importance.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The independent genre of biography as distinct from general history writing, began to emerge in the 18th century and reached its contemporary form at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biography is the earliest literary genre in history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] According to Egyptologist Miriam Lichtheim, writing took its first steps toward literature in the context of the private tomb funerary inscriptions.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] These were commemorative biographical texts recounting the careers of deceased high royal officials.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The earliest biographical texts are from the 26th century BC.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In the 21st century BC, another famous biography was composed in Mesopotamia about Gilgamesh.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] One of the five versions could be historical.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] From the same region a couple of centuries later, according to another famous biography, departed Abraham.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] He and his three descendants became subjects of ancient Hebrew biographies whether fictional or historical.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] 430 to 355/354 BC) wrote the biography of Cyrus, the founder of the Persian Empire.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] One of the earliest Roman biographers was Cornelius Nepos, who published his work *Excellentium Imperatorum Vitae* ("Lives of outstanding generals") in 44 BC.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Longer and more extensive biographies were written in Greek by Plutarch, in his *Parallel Lives*, published about 80 AD.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In this work famous Greeks are paired with famous Romans, for example, the orators Demosthenes and Cicero, or the generals Alexander the Great and Julius Caesar; some fifty biographies from the work survive.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Another well-known collection of ancient biographies is *De vita Caesarum* ("On the Lives of the Caesars") by Suetonius, written about 121 AD in the time of the emperor Hadrian.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Meanwhile, in the eastern imperial periphery, Gospel described the life of Jesus.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In the early Middle Ages (400–1450 AD), there was a decline in awareness of the classical culture in Europe.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] During this time, the only repositories of knowledge and records of the early history in Europe were those of the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Hermits, monks, and priests used this historic period to write biographies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Their subjects were usually restricted to the church fathers, martyrs, popes, and saints.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Their works were meant to be inspirational to the people and vehicles for conversion to Christianity (see Hagiography).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] One significant secular example of a biography from this period is the life of Charlemagne by his courtier Einhard.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In Medieval Western India, there was a Sanskrit Jain literary genre of writing semi-historical biographical narratives about the lives of famous persons called Prabandhas.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Prabandhas were written primarily by Jain scholars from the 13th century onwards and were written in colloquial Sanskrit (as opposed to Classical Sanskrit).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The earliest collection explicitly titled *Prabandha* is Jinabhadra's *Prabandhavali* (1234 CE).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] AD 750 to 1258), similar traditional Muslim biographies of Muhammad and other important figures in the early history of Islam began to be written, beginning the Prophetic biography tradition.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Early biographical dictionaries were published as compendia of famous Islamic personalities from the 9th century onwards.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] They contained more social data for a large segment of the population than other works of that period.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The earliest biographical dictionaries initially focused on the lives of the prophets of Islam and their companions, with one of these early examples being *The Book of The Major Classes* by Ibn Sa'd al-Baghdadi.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] And then began the documentation of the lives of many other historical figures (from rulers to scholars) who lived in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] By the late Middle Ages, biographies became less church-oriented in Europe as biographies of kings, knights, and tyrants began to appear.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The most famous of such biographies was *Le Morte d'Arthur* by Sir Thomas Malory.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The book was an account of the life of the fabled King Arthur and his Knights of the Round Table.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Following Malory, the new emphasis on humanism during the Renaissance promoted a focus on secular subjects, such as artists and poets, and encouraged writing in the vernacular.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Giorgio Vasari's *Lives of the Artists* (1550) was the landmark biography focusing on secular lives.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Vasari made celebrities of his subjects, as the *Lives* became an early "bestseller".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Two other developments are noteworthy: the development of the printing press in the 15th century and the gradual increase in literacy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biographies in the English language began appearing during the reign of Henry VIII.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] John Foxe's *Actes and Monuments* (1563), better known as *Foxe's Book of Martyrs*, was essentially the first dictionary of the biography in Europe, followed by Thomas Fuller's *The History of the Worthies of England* (1662), with a distinct focus on public life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Influential in shaping popular conceptions of pirates, *A General History of the Pyrates* (1724), by Charles Johnson, is the prime source for the biographies of many well-known pirates.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] A notable early collection of biographies of eminent men and women in the United Kingdom was *Biographia Britannica* (1747–1766) edited by William Oldys.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The American biography followed the English model, incorporating Thomas Carlyle's view that biography was a part of history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Carlyle asserted that the lives of great human beings were essential to understanding society and its institutions.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] While the historical impulse would remain a strong element in early American biography, American writers carved out a distinct approach.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] What emerged was a rather didactic form of biography, which sought to shape the individual character of a reader in the process of defining national character.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The first modern biography, and a work that exerted considerable influence on the evolution of the genre, was James Boswell's *The Life of Samuel Johnson*, a biography of lexicographer and man-of-letters Samuel Johnson published in 1791.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] While Boswell's personal acquaintance with his subject only began in 1763, when Johnson was 54 years old, Boswell covered the entirety of Johnson's life by means of additional research.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Itself an important stage in the development of the modern genre of biography, it has been claimed to be the greatest biography written in the English language.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biographical writing generally stagnated during the 19th century – in many cases there was a reversal to the more familiar hagiographical method of eulogizing the dead, similar to the biographies of saints produced in Medieval times.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] A distinction between mass biography and literary biography began to form by the middle of the century, reflecting a breach between high culture and middle-class culture.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] However, the number of biographies in print experienced a rapid growth, thanks to an expanding reading public.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] This revolution in publishing made books available to a larger audience of readers.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In addition, affordable paperback editions of popular biographies were published for the first time.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Periodicals began publishing a sequence of biographical sketches.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Autobiographies became more popular, as with the rise of education and cheap printing, modern concepts of fame and celebrity began to develop.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The sciences of psychology and sociology were ascendant at the turn of the 20th century and would heavily influence the new century's biographies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The demise of the "great man" theory of history was indicative of the emerging mindset.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Human behavior would be explained through Darwinian theories.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] "Sociological" biographies conceived of their subjects' actions as the result of the environment, and tended to downplay individuality.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The development of psychoanalysis led to a more penetrating and comprehensive understanding of the biographical subject, and induced biographers to give more emphasis to childhood and adolescence.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Clearly these psychological ideas were changing the way biographies were written, as a culture of autobiography developed, in which the telling of one's own story became a form of therapy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The conventional concept of heroes and narratives of success disappeared in the obsession with psychological explorations of personality.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] British critic Lytton Strachey revolutionized the art of biographical writing with his 1918 work *Eminent Victorians*, consisting of biographies of four leading figures from the Victorian era: Cardinal Manning, Florence Nightingale, Thomas Arnold, and General Gordon.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Strachey set out to breathe life into the Victorian era for future generations to read.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] His narrative demolished the myths that had built up around these cherished national heroes, whom he regarded as no better than a "set of mouth bungled hypocrites".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The book achieved worldwide fame due to its irreverent and witty style, its concise and factually accurate nature, and its artistic prose.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In the 1920s and 1930s, biographical writers sought to capitalize on Strachey's popularity by imitating his style.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] This new school featured iconoclasts, scientific analysts, and fictional biographers and included Gamaliel Bradford, André Maurois, and Emil Ludwig, among others.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Robert Graves (*I, Claudius*, 1934) stood out among those following Strachey's model of "debunking biographies." The trend in literary biography was accompanied in popular biography by a sort of "celebrity voyeurism", in the early decades of the century.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] This latter form's appeal to readers was based on curiosity more than morality or patriotism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] By World War I, cheap hard-cover reprints had become popular.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] American professional historiography gives a limited role to biography, preferring instead to emphasize deeper social and cultural influences.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Political biographers historically incorporated moralizing judgments into their work, with scholarly biography being an uncommon genre before the mid-1920s.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Allan Nevins was a major contributor in the 1930s to the multi-volume *Dictionary of American Biography*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Nevins also sponsored a series of long political biographies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Later biographers sought to show how political figures balanced power and responsibility.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] However, many biographers found that their subjects were not as morally pure as they originally thought, and young historians after 1960 tended to be more critical.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The exception is Robert Remini whose books on Andrew Jackson idolize its hero and fends off criticisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The study of decision-making in politics is important for scholarly political biographers, who can take different approaches such as focusing on psychology/personality, bureaucracy/interests, fundamental ideas, or societal forces.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] However, most documentation favors the first approach, which emphasizes personalities.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biographers often neglect the voting blocs and legislative positions of politicians and the organizational structures of bureaucracies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] A more promising approach is to locate a person's ideas through intellectual history, but this has become more difficult with the philosophical shallowness of political figures in recent times.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Political biography can be frustrating and challenging to integrate with other fields of political history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The feminist scholar Carolyn Heilbrun observed that women's biographies and autobiographies began to change character during the second wave of feminist activism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In recent years, multimedia biography has become more popular than traditional literary forms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Along with documentary biographical films, Hollywood produced numerous commercial films based on the lives of famous people.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The popularity of these forms of biography have led to the proliferation of TV channels dedicated to biography, including A&E, The Biography Channel, and The History Channel.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] CD-ROM and online biographies have also appeared.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Unlike books and films, they often do not tell a chronological narrative: instead they are archives of many discrete media elements related to an individual person, including video clips, photographs, and text articles.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biography-Portraits were created in 2001, by the German artist Ralph Ueltzhoeffer.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Media scholar Lev Manovich says that such archives exemplify the database form, allowing users to navigate the materials in many ways.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] General "life writing" techniques are a subject of scholarly study.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] In recent years, debates have arisen as to whether all biographies are fiction, especially when authors are writing about figures from the past.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] President of Wolfson College at Oxford University, Hermione Lee argues that all history is seen through a perspective that is the product of one's contemporary society and as a result, biographical truths are constantly shifting.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] So, the history biographers write about will not be the way that it happened; it will be the way they remembered it.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Debates have also arisen concerning the importance of space in life-writing.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biography Studies is emerging as an independent discipline, especially in the Netherlands.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] This Dutch School of biography is moving biography studies away from the less scholarly life writing tradition and towards history by encouraging its practitioners to utilize an approach adapted from microhistory.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] Biographical research is defined by Miller as a research method that collects and analyses a person's whole life, or portion of a life, through the in-depth and unstructured interview, or sometimes reinforced by semi-structured interview or personal documents.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] It is a way of viewing social life in procedural terms, rather than static terms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The information can come from "oral history, personal narrative, biography and autobiography" or "diaries, letters, memoranda and other materials".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] The central aim of biographical research is to produce rich descriptions of persons or "conceptualise structural types of actions", which means to "understand the action logics or how persons and structures are interlinked".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] This method can be used to understand an individual's life within its social context or understand the cultural phenomena.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/biography] There are many largely unacknowledged pitfalls to writing good biographies, and these largely concern the relation between firstly the individual and the context, and, secondly, the private and public.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, new techniques were developed for the study of plants, including methods of optical microscopy and live cell imaging, electron microscopy, analysis of chromosome number, plant chemistry and the structure and function of enzymes and other proteins.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In the last two decades of the 20th century, botanists exploited the techniques of molecular genetic analysis, including genomics and proteomics and DNA sequences to classify plants more accurately.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Modern botany is a broad subject with contributions and insights from most other areas of science and technology.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Research topics include the study of plant structure, growth and differentiation, reproduction, biochemistry and primary metabolism, chemical products, development, diseases, evolutionary relationships, systematics, and plant taxonomy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Dominant themes in 21st-century plant science are molecular genetics and epigenetics, which study the mechanisms and control of gene expression during differentiation of plant cells and tissues.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The term "botany" comes from the Ancient Greek word **botanē** (βοτάνη) meaning "pasture", "herbs" "grass", or "fodder"; **Botanē** is in turn derived from **boskein** (Greek: βόσκειν), "to feed" or "to graze".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Traditionally, botany has also included the study of fungi and algae by mycologists and phycologists respectively, with the study of these three groups of organisms remaining within the sphere of interest of the International Botanical Congress.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botany originated as herbalism, the study and use of plants for their possible medicinal properties.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The early recorded history of botany includes many ancient writings and plant classifications.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Examples of early botanical works have been found in ancient texts from India dating back to before 1100 BCE, Ancient Egypt, in archaic Avestan writings, and in works from China purportedly from before 221 BCE.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Modern botany traces its roots back to Ancient Greece specifically to Theophrastus (c.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] 371–287 BCE), a student of Aristotle who invented and described many of its principles and is widely regarded in the scientific community as the "Father of Botany".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] His major works, *Enquiry into Plants* and *On the Causes of Plants*, constitute the most important contributions to botanical science until the Middle Ages, almost seventeen centuries later.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Another work from Ancient Greece that made an early impact on botany is *De materia medica*, a five-volume encyclopaedia about preliminary herbal medicine written in the middle of the first century by Greek physician and pharmacologist Pedanius Dioscorides.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] *De materia medica* was widely read for more than 1,500 years.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Important contributions from the medieval Muslim world include Ibn Wahshiyya's *Nabatean Agriculture*, Abū Ḥanīfa Dīnawarī's (828–896) the *Book of Plants*, and Ibn Bassal's *The Classification of Soils*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In the early 13th century, Abu al-Abbas al-Nabati, and Ibn al-Baitar (d.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] 1248) wrote on botany in a systematic and scientific manner.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In the mid-16th century, botanical gardens were founded in a number of Italian universities.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The Padua botanical garden in 1545 is usually considered to be the first that is still in its original location.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These gardens continued the practical value of earlier "physic gardens", often associated with monasteries, in which plants were cultivated for suspected medicinal uses.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] They supported the growth of botany as an academic subject.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Lectures were given about the plants grown in the gardens.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botanical gardens came much later to northern Europe; the first in England was the University of Oxford Botanic Garden in 1621.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] German physician Leonhart Fuchs (1501–1566) was one of "the three German fathers of botany", along with theologian Otto Brunfels (1489–1534) and physician Hieronymus Bock (1498–1554) (also called Hieronymus Tragus).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Fuchs and Brunfels broke away from the tradition of copying earlier works to make original observations of their own.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Bock created his own system of plant classification.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Physician Valerius Cordus (1515–1544) authored a botanically and pharmacologically important herbal *Historia Plantarum* in 1544 and a pharmacopoeia of lasting importance, the *Dispensatorium* in 1546.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Naturalist Conrad von Gesner (1516–1565) and herbalist John Gerard (1545 – c.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] 1611) published herbals covering the supposed medicinal uses of plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Naturalist Ulisse Aldrovandi (1522–1605) was considered the *father of natural history*, which included the study of plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In 1665, using an early microscope, Polymath Robert Hooke discovered cells (a term he coined) in cork, and a short time later in living plant tissue.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] During the 18th century, systems of plant identification were developed comparable to dichotomous keys, where unidentified plants are placed into taxonomic groups (e.g. family, genus and species) by making a series of choices between pairs of characters.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The choice and sequence of the characters may be artificial in keys designed purely for identification (diagnostic keys) or more closely related to the natural or phyletic order of the taxa in synoptic keys.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] By the 18th century, new plants for study were arriving in Europe in increasing numbers from newly discovered countries and the European colonies worldwide.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In 1753, Carl Linnaeus published his Species Plantarum, a hierarchical classification of plant species that remains the reference point for modern botanical nomenclature.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This established a standardised binomial or two-part naming scheme where the first name represented the genus and the second identified the species within the genus.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For the purposes of identification, Linnaeus's *Systema Sexuale* classified plants into 24 groups according to the number of their male sexual organs.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The 24th group, *Cryptogamia*, included all plants with concealed reproductive parts: mosses, liverworts, ferns, algae and fungi.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Increasing knowledge of plant anatomy, morphology and life cycles led to the realisation that there were more natural affinities between plants than the artificial sexual system of Linnaeus.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Adanson (1763), de Jussieu (1789), and Candolle (1819) all proposed various alternative natural systems of classification that grouped plants using a wider range of shared characters and were widely followed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The Candollean system reflected his ideas of the progression of morphological complexity and the later Bentham & Hooker system, which was influential until the mid-19th century, was influenced by Candolle's approach.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Darwin's publication of the *Origin of Species* in 1859 and his concept of common descent required modifications to the Candollean system to reflect evolutionary relationships as distinct from mere morphological similarity.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In the 19th century botany was a socially acceptable hobby for upper-class women.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These women would collect and paint flowers and plants from around the world with scientific accuracy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The paintings were used to record many species that could not be transported or maintained in other environments.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Marianne North illustrated over 900 species in extreme detail with watercolour and oil paintings.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Her work and many other women's botany work was the beginning of popularising botany to a wider audience.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botany was greatly stimulated by the appearance of the first "modern" textbook, Matthias Schleiden's **Grundzüge der Wissenschaftlichen Botanik**, published in English in 1849 as *Principles of Scientific Botany*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Schleiden was a microscopist and an early plant anatomist who co-founded the cell theory with Theodor Schwann and Rudolf Virchow and was among the first to grasp the significance of the cell nucleus that had been described by Robert Brown in 1831.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In 1855, Adolf Fick formulated Fick's laws that enabled the calculation of the rates of molecular diffusion in biological systems.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Building upon the gene-chromosome theory of heredity that originated with Gregor Mendel (1822–1884), August Weismann (1834–1914) proved that inheritance only takes place through gametes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] No other cells can pass on inherited characters.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The work of Katherine Esau (1898–1997) on plant anatomy is still a major foundation of modern botany.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Her books *Plant Anatomy* and *Anatomy of Seed Plants* have been key plant structural biology texts for more than half a century.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The discipline of plant ecology was pioneered in the late 19th century by botanists such as Eugenius Warming, who produced the hypothesis that plants form communities, and his mentor and successor Christen C.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Raunkiær whose system for describing plant life forms is still in use today.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The concept that the composition of plant communities such as temperate broadleaf forest changes by a process of ecological succession was developed by Henry Chandler Cowles, Arthur Tansley and Frederic Clements.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Clements is credited with the idea of climax vegetation as the most complex vegetation that an environment can support and Tansley introduced the concept of ecosystems to biology.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Building on the extensive earlier work of Alphonse de Candolle, Nikolai Vavilov (1887–1943) produced accounts of the biogeography, centres of origin, and evolutionary history of economic plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These developments, coupled with new methods for measuring the size of stomatal apertures, and the rate of photosynthesis have enabled a precise description of the rates of gas exchange between plants and the atmosphere.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Innovations in statistical analysis by Ronald Fisher, Frank Yates and others at Rothamsted Experimental Station facilitated rational experimental design and data analysis in botanical research.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The discovery and identification of the auxin plant hormones by Kenneth V.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Thimann in 1948 enabled the regulation of plant growth by externally applied chemicals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Frederick Campion Steward pioneered techniques of micropropagation and plant tissue culture controlled by plant hormones.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The synthetic auxin 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid or 2,4-D was one of the first commercial synthetic herbicides.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] 20th century developments in plant biochemistry have been driven by modern techniques of organic chemical analysis, such as spectroscopy, chromatography and electrophoresis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These technologies enable the biotechnological use of whole plants or plant cell cultures grown in bioreactors to synthesise pesticides, antibiotics or other pharmaceuticals, as well as the practical application of genetically modified crops designed for traits such as improved yield.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Modern morphology recognises a continuum between the major morphological categories of root, stem (caulome), leaf (phyllome) and trichome.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Furthermore, it emphasises structural dynamics.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Modern systematics aims to reflect and discover phylogenetic relationships between plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Modern molecular phylogenetics largely ignores morphological characters, relying on DNA sequences as data.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Molecular analysis of DNA sequences from most families of flowering plants enabled the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group to publish in 1998 a phylogeny of flowering plants, answering many of the questions about relationships among angiosperm families and species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The theoretical possibility of a practical method for the identification of plant species and commercial varieties by DNA barcoding is the subject of active current research.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some subfields of botany relate to particular groups of organisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Divisions related to the broader historical sense of botany include *bacteriology*, *mycology* (or *fungology*), and *phycology* – respectively, the study of bacteria, fungi, and algae – with *lichenology* as a subfield of mycology.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The narrower sense of botany as the study of embryophytes (land plants) is called *phytology*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] *Bryology* is the study of mosses (and in the broader sense also liverworts and hornworts).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] *Pteridology* (or *filicology*) is the study of ferns and allied plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] A number of other taxa of ranks varying from family to subgenus have terms for their study, including *agrostology* (or *graminology*) for the study of grasses, *synantherology* for the study of composites, and *batology* for the study of brambles.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Study can also be divided by guild rather than clade or grade.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For example, *dendrology* is the study of woody plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Many divisions of biology have botanical subfields.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These are commonly denoted by prefixing the word plant (e.g. plant taxonomy, plant ecology, plant anatomy, plant morphology, plant systematics), or prefixing or substituting the prefix phyto- (e.g. phytochemistry, phytogeography).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The study of fossil plants is called *palaeobotany*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Other fields are denoted by adding or substituting the word botany (e.g. systematic botany).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The intersection of fields from the above pair of categories gives rise to fields such as *bryogeography*, the study of the distribution of mosses.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Different parts of plants also give rise to their own subfields, including *xylology*, *carpology* (or *fructology*), and *palynology*, these being the study of wood, fruit and pollen/spores respectively.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botany also overlaps on the one hand with agriculture, horticulture and silviculture, and on the other hand with medicine and pharmacology, giving rise to fields such as *agronomy*, *horticultural botany*, *phytopathology*, and *phytopharmacology*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The study of plants is vital because they underpin almost all animal life on Earth by generating a large proportion of the oxygen and food that provide humans and other organisms with aerobic respiration with the chemical energy they need to exist.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] As a by-product of photosynthesis, plants release oxygen into the atmosphere, a gas that is required by nearly all living things to carry out cellular respiration.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In addition, they are influential in the global carbon and water cycles and plant roots bind and stabilise soils, preventing soil erosion.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants are crucial to the future of human society as they provide food, oxygen, biochemicals, and products for people, as well as creating and preserving soil.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Historically, all living things were classified as either animals or plants and botany covered the study of all organisms not considered animals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botanists examine both the internal functions and processes within plant organelles, cells, tissues, whole plants, plant populations and plant communities.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] At each of these levels, a botanist may be concerned with the classification (taxonomy), phylogeny and evolution, structure (anatomy and morphology), or function (physiology) of plant life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The strictest definition of "plant" includes only the "land plants" or embryophytes, which include seed plants (gymnosperms, including the pines, and flowering plants) and the free-sporing cryptogams including ferns, clubmosses, liverworts, hornworts and mosses.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Embryophytes are multicellular eukaryotes descended from an ancestor that obtained its energy from sunlight by photosynthesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] They have life cycles with alternating haploid and diploid phases.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The sexual haploid phase of embryophytes, known as the gametophyte, nurtures the developing diploid embryo sporophyte within its tissues for at least part of its life, even in the seed plants, where the gametophyte itself is nurtured by its parent sporophyte.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Other groups of organisms that were previously studied by botanists include bacteria (now studied in bacteriology), fungi (mycology) – including lichen-forming fungi (lichenology), non-chlorophyte algae (phycology), and viruses (virology).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] However, attention is still given to these groups by botanists, and fungi (including lichens) and photosynthetic protists are usually covered in introductory botany courses.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Palaeobotanists study ancient plants in the fossil record to provide information about the evolutionary history of plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Cyanobacteria, the first oxygen-releasing photosynthetic organisms on Earth, are thought to have given rise to the ancestor of plants by entering into an endosymbiotic relationship with an early eukaryote, ultimately becoming the chloroplasts in plant cells.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The new photosynthetic plants (along with their algal relatives) accelerated the rise in atmospheric oxygen started by the cyanobacteria, changing the ancient oxygen-free, reducing, atmosphere to one in which free oxygen has been abundant for more than 2 billion years.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Virtually all staple foods come either directly from primary production by plants, or indirectly from animals that eat them.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants and other photosynthetic organisms are at the base of most food chains because they use the energy from the sun and nutrients from the soil and atmosphere, converting them into a form that can be used by animals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This is what ecologists call the first trophic level.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botanists study how plants produce food and how to increase yields, for example through plant breeding, making their work important to humanity's ability to feed the world and provide food security for future generations.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Botanists also study weeds, which are a considerable problem in agriculture, and the biology and control of plant pathogens in agriculture and natural ecosystems.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Ethnobotany is the study of the relationships between plants and people.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] When applied to the investigation of historical plant–people relationships ethnobotany may be referred to as archaeobotany or palaeoethnobotany.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plant biochemistry is the study of the chemical processes used by plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some of these processes are used in their primary metabolism like the photosynthetic Calvin cycle and crassulacean acid metabolism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Others make specialised materials like the cellulose and lignin used to build their bodies, and secondary products like resins and aroma compounds.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants and various other groups of photosynthetic eukaryotes collectively known as "algae" have unique organelles known as chloroplasts.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Chloroplasts are thought to be descended from cyanobacteria that formed endosymbiotic relationships with ancient plant and algal ancestors.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Chloroplasts and cyanobacteria contain the blue-green pigment chlorophyll *a*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Chlorophyll *a* (as well as its plant and green algal-specific cousin chlorophyll *b*) absorbs light in the blue-violet and orange/red parts of the spectrum while reflecting and transmitting the green light that we see as the characteristic colour of these organisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The energy in the red and blue light that these pigments absorb is used by chloroplasts to make energy-rich carbon compounds from carbon dioxide and water by oxygenic photosynthesis, a process that generates molecular oxygen (O2) as a by-product.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The light energy captured by chlorophyll *a* is initially in the form of electrons (and later a proton gradient) that is used to make molecules of ATP and NADPH which temporarily store and transport energy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Their energy is used in the light-independent reactions of the Calvin cycle by the enzyme rubisco to produce molecules of the 3-carbon sugar glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is the first product of photosynthesis and the raw material from which glucose and almost all other organic molecules of biological origin are synthesised.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some of the glucose is converted to starch which is stored in the chloroplast.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Starch is the characteristic energy store of most land plants and algae, while inulin, a polymer of fructose is used for the same purpose in the sunflower family Asteraceae.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some of the glucose is converted to sucrose (common table sugar) for export to the rest of the plant.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Unlike in animals (which lack chloroplasts), plants and their eukaryote relatives have delegated many biochemical roles to their chloroplasts, including synthesising all their fatty acids, and most amino acids.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The fatty acids that chloroplasts make are used for many things, such as providing material to build cell membranes out of and making the polymer cutin which is found in the plant cuticle that protects land plants from drying out.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants synthesise a number of unique polymers like the polysaccharide molecules cellulose, pectin and xyloglucan from which the land plant cell wall is constructed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Vascular land plants make lignin, a polymer used to strengthen the secondary cell walls of xylem tracheids and vessels to keep them from collapsing when a plant sucks water through them under water stress.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Lignin is also used in other cell types like sclerenchyma fibres that provide structural support for a plant and is a major constituent of wood.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Sporopollenin is a chemically resistant polymer found in the outer cell walls of spores and pollen of land plants responsible for the survival of early land plant spores and the pollen of seed plants in the fossil record.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] It is widely regarded as a marker for the start of land plant evolution during the Ordovician period.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere today is much lower than it was when plants emerged onto land during the Ordovician and Silurian periods.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These biochemical strategies are unique to land plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Phytochemistry is a branch of plant biochemistry primarily concerned with the chemical substances produced by plants during secondary metabolism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some of these compounds are toxins such as the alkaloid coniine from hemlock.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Others, such as the essential oils peppermint oil and lemon oil are useful for their aroma, as flavourings and spices (e.g., capsaicin), and in medicine as pharmaceuticals as in opium from opium poppies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Many medicinal and recreational drugs, such as tetrahydrocannabinol (active ingredient in cannabis), caffeine, morphine and nicotine come directly from plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Others are simple derivatives of botanical natural products.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For example, the pain killer aspirin is the acetyl ester of salicylic acid, originally isolated from the bark of willow trees, and a wide range of opiate painkillers like heroin are obtained by chemical modification of morphine obtained from the opium poppy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Popular stimulants come from plants, such as caffeine from coffee, tea and chocolate, and nicotine from tobacco.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Most alcoholic beverages come from fermentation of carbohydrate-rich plant products such as barley (beer), rice (sake) and grapes (wine).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Native Americans have used various plants as ways of treating illness or disease for thousands of years.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This knowledge Native Americans have on plants has been recorded by enthnobotanists and then in turn has been used by pharmaceutical companies as a way of drug discovery.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Sugar, starch, cotton, linen, hemp, some types of rope, wood and particle boards, papyrus and paper, vegetable oils, wax, and natural rubber are examples of commercially important materials made from plant tissues or their secondary products.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Charcoal, a pure form of carbon made by pyrolysis of wood, has a long history as a metal-smelting fuel, as a filter material and adsorbent and as an artist's material and is one of the three ingredients of gunpowder.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Cellulose, the world's most abundant organic polymer, can be converted into energy, fuels, materials and chemical feedstock.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Products made from cellulose include rayon and cellophane, wallpaper paste, biobutanol and gun cotton.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Sugarcane, rapeseed and soy are some of the plants with a highly fermentable sugar or oil content that are used as sources of biofuels, important alternatives to fossil fuels, such as biodiesel.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Sweetgrass was used by Native Americans to ward off bugs like mosquitoes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These bug repelling properties of sweetgrass were later found by the American Chemical Society in the molecules phytol and coumarin.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plant ecology is the science of the functional relationships between plants and their habitats – the environments where they complete their life cycles.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plant ecologists study the composition of local and regional floras, their biodiversity, genetic diversity and fitness, the adaptation of plants to their environment, and their competitive or mutualistic interactions with other species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some ecologists even rely on empirical data from indigenous people that is gathered by ethnobotanists.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This information can relay a great deal of information on how the land once was, thousands of years ago, and how it has changed over that time.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The goals of plant ecology are to understand the causes of their distribution patterns, productivity, environmental impact, evolution, and responses to environmental change.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants depend on certain edaphic (soil) and climatic factors in their environment but can modify these factors too.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For example, they can change their environment's albedo, increase runoff interception, stabilise mineral soils and develop their organic content, and affect local temperature.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plants compete with other organisms in their ecosystem for resources.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] They interact with their neighbours at a variety of spatial scales in groups, populations and communities that collectively constitute vegetation.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Regions with characteristic vegetation types and dominant plants as well as similar abiotic and biotic factors, climate, and geography make up biomes like tundra or tropical rainforest.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Herbivores eat plants, but plants can defend themselves, and some species are parasitic or even carnivorous.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Other organisms form mutually beneficial relationships with plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For example, mycorrhizal fungi and rhizobia provide plants with nutrients in exchange for food; ants are recruited by ant plants to provide protection; honey bees, bats and other animals pollinate flowers; and humans and other animals act as dispersal vectors to spread spores and seeds.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Plant responses to climate and other environmental changes can inform one's understanding of how these changes affect ecosystem function and productivity.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] For example, plant phenology can be a useful proxy for temperature in historical climatology, and the biological impact of climate change and global warming.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Palynology, the analysis of fossil pollen deposits in sediments from thousands or millions of years ago allows the reconstruction of past climates.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Estimates of atmospheric CO2 concentrations since the Palaeozoic have been obtained from stomatal densities and the leaf shapes and sizes of ancient land plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Ozone depletion can expose plants to higher levels of ultraviolet radiation-B (UV-B), resulting in lower growth rates.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Moreover, information from studies of community ecology, plant systematics, and taxonomy is essential to understanding vegetation change, habitat destruction and species extinction.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Inheritance in plants follows the same fundamental principles of genetics as in other multicellular organisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Gregor Mendel discovered the genetic laws of inheritance by studying inherited traits such as shape in *Pisum sativum* (peas).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] What Mendel learned from studying plants has had far-reaching benefits outside of botany.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Similarly, "jumping genes" were discovered by Barbara McClintock while she was studying maize.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Nevertheless, there are some distinctive genetic differences between plants and other organisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Species boundaries in plants may be weaker than in animals, and cross species hybrids are often possible.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] A familiar example is peppermint, *Mentha* × *piperita*, a sterile hybrid between *Mentha aquatica* and spearmint, *Mentha spicata*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The many cultivated varieties of wheat are the result of multiple inter- and intra-specific crosses between wild species and their hybrids.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Angiosperms with monoecious flowers often have self-incompatibility mechanisms that operate between the pollen and stigma so that the pollen either fails to reach the stigma or fails to germinate and produce male gametes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This is one of several methods used by plants to promote outcrossing.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] In many land plants the male and female gametes are produced by separate individuals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These species are said to be dioecious when referring to vascular plant sporophytes and dioicous when referring to bryophyte gametophytes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This beneficial effect is also known as hybrid vigour or heterosis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Once outcrossing is established, subsequent switching to inbreeding becomes disadvantageous since it allows expression of the previously masked deleterious recessive mutations, commonly referred to as inbreeding depression.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Unlike in higher animals, where parthenogenesis is rare, asexual reproduction may occur in plants by several different mechanisms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The formation of stem tubers in potato is one example.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Particularly in arctic or alpine habitats, where opportunities for fertilisation of flowers by animals are rare, plantlets or bulbs may develop instead of flowers, replacing sexual reproduction with asexual reproduction and giving rise to clonal populations genetically identical to the parent.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This is one of several types of apomixis that occur in plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Apomixis can also happen in a seed, producing a seed that contains an embryo genetically identical to the parent.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Most sexually reproducing organisms are diploid, with paired chromosomes, but doubling of their chromosome number may occur due to errors in cytokinesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] This can occur early in development to produce an autopolyploid or partly autopolyploid organism, or during normal processes of cellular differentiation to produce some cell types that are polyploid (endopolyploidy), or during gamete formation.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] An allopolyploid plant may result from a hybridisation event between two different species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Both autopolyploid and allopolyploid plants can often reproduce normally, but may be unable to cross-breed successfully with the parent population because there is a mismatch in chromosome numbers.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These plants that are reproductively isolated from the parent species but live within the same geographical area, may be sufficiently successful to form a new species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some otherwise sterile plant polyploids can still reproduce vegetatively or by seed apomixis, forming clonal populations of identical individuals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Durum wheat is a fertile tetraploid allopolyploid, while bread wheat is a fertile hexaploid.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The commercial banana is an example of a sterile, seedless triploid hybrid.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Common dandelion is a triploid that produces viable seeds by apomictic seed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] As in other eukaryotes, the inheritance of endosymbiotic organelles like mitochondria and chloroplasts in plants is non-Mendelian.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Chloroplasts are inherited through the male parent in gymnosperms but often through the female parent in flowering plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] A considerable amount of new knowledge about plant function comes from studies of the molecular genetics of model plants such as the Thale cress, *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a weedy species in the mustard family (Brassicaceae).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The genome or hereditary information contained in the genes of this species is encoded by about 135 million base pairs of DNA, forming one of the smallest genomes among flowering plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] *Arabidopsis* was the first plant to have its genome sequenced, in 2000.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The sequencing of some other relatively small genomes, of rice (*Oryza sativa*) and *Brachypodium distachyon*, has made them important model species for understanding the genetics, cellular and molecular biology of cereals, grasses and monocots generally.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Model plants such as *Arabidopsis thaliana* are used for studying the molecular biology of plant cells and the chloroplast.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Ideally, these organisms have small genomes that are well known or completely sequenced, small stature and short generation times.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Corn has been used to study mechanisms of photosynthesis and phloem loading of sugar in C4 plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The single-celled green alga *Chlamydomonas reinhardtii*, while not an embryophyte itself, contains a green-pigmented chloroplast related to that of land plants, making it useful for study.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] A red alga, *Cyanidioschyzon merolae*, has also been used to study some basic chloroplast functions.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Spinach, peas, soybeans and a moss *Physcomitrella patens* are commonly used to study plant cell biology.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Epigenetics is the study of heritable changes in gene function that cannot be explained by changes in the underlying DNA sequence but cause the organism's genes to behave (or "express themselves") differently.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] One example of epigenetic change is the marking of the genes by DNA methylation which determines whether they will be expressed or not.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Gene expression can also be controlled by repressor proteins that attach to silencer regions of the DNA and prevent that region of the DNA code from being expressed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Epigenetic marks may be added or removed from the DNA during programmed stages of development of the plant, and are responsible, for example, for the differences between anthers, petals and normal leaves, despite the fact that they all have the same underlying genetic code.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Epigenetic changes may be temporary or may remain through successive cell divisions for the remainder of the cell's life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Some epigenetic changes have been shown to be heritable, while others are reset in the germ cells.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Epigenetic changes in eukaryotic biology serve to regulate the process of cellular differentiation.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] During morphogenesis, totipotent stem cells become the various pluripotent cell lines of the embryo, which in turn become fully differentiated cells.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] A single fertilised egg cell, the zygote, gives rise to the many different plant cell types including parenchyma, xylem vessel elements, phloem sieve tubes, guard cells of the epidermis, etc. as it continues to divide.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The process results from the epigenetic activation of some genes and inhibition of others.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Unlike animals, many plant cells, particularly those of the parenchyma, do not terminally differentiate, remaining totipotent with the ability to give rise to a new individual plant.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Exceptions include highly lignified cells, the sclerenchyma and xylem which are dead at maturity, and the phloem sieve tubes which lack nuclei.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] While plants use many of the same epigenetic mechanisms as animals, such as chromatin remodelling, an alternative hypothesis is that plants set their gene expression patterns using positional information from the environment and surrounding cells to determine their developmental fate.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Epigenetic changes can lead to paramutations, which do not follow the Mendelian heritage rules.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] These epigenetic marks are carried from one generation to the next, with one allele inducing a change on the other.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The algae are a polyphyletic group and are placed in various divisions, some more closely related to plants than others.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] There are many differences between them in features such as cell wall composition, biochemistry, pigmentation, chloroplast structure and nutrient reserves.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The algal division Charophyta, sister to the green algal division Chlorophyta, is considered to contain the ancestor of true plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The Charophyte class Charophyceae and the land plant sub-kingdom Embryophyta together form the monophyletic group or clade Streptophytina.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Nonvascular land plants are embryophytes that lack the vascular tissues xylem and phloem.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] They include mosses, liverworts and hornworts.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Pteridophytic vascular plants with true xylem and phloem that reproduced by spores germinating into free-living gametophytes evolved during the Silurian period and diversified into several lineages during the late Silurian and early Devonian.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Representatives of the lycopods have survived to the present day.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] By the end of the Devonian period, several groups, including the lycopods, sphenophylls and progymnosperms, had independently evolved "megaspory" – their spores were of two distinct sizes, larger megaspores and smaller microspores.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Their reduced gametophytes developed from megaspores retained within the spore-producing organs (megasporangia) of the sporophyte, a condition known as endospory.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Seeds consist of an endosporic megasporangium surrounded by one or two sheathing layers (integuments).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The young sporophyte develops within the seed, which on germination splits to release it.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] The earliest known seed plants date from the latest Devonian Famennian stage.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Following the evolution of the seed habit, seed plants diversified, giving rise to a number of now-extinct groups, including seed ferns, as well as the modern gymnosperms and angiosperms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Gymnosperms produce "naked seeds" not fully enclosed in an ovary; modern representatives include conifers, cycads, *Ginkgo*, and Gnetales.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Angiosperms produce seeds enclosed in a structure such as a carpel or an ovary.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p01] Ongoing research on the molecular phylogenetics of living plants appears to show that the angiosperms are a sister clade to the gymnosperms.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Plant physiology encompasses all the internal chemical and physical activities of plants associated with life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Chemicals obtained from the air, soil and water form the basis of all plant metabolism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The energy of sunlight, captured by oxygenic photosynthesis and released by cellular respiration, is the basis of almost all life.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Photoautotrophs, including all green plants, algae and cyanobacteria gather energy directly from sunlight by photosynthesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Heterotrophs including all animals, all fungi, all completely parasitic plants, and non-photosynthetic bacteria take in organic molecules produced by photoautotrophs and respire them or use them in the construction of cells and tissues.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Respiration is the oxidation of carbon compounds by breaking them down into simpler structures to release the energy they contain, essentially the opposite of photosynthesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Molecules are moved within plants by transport processes that operate at a variety of spatial scales.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Subcellular transport of ions, electrons and molecules such as water and enzymes occurs across cell membranes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Minerals and water are transported from roots to other parts of the plant in the transpiration stream.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Diffusion, osmosis, and active transport and mass flow are all different ways transport can occur.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Examples of elements that plants need to transport are nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulphur.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In vascular plants, these elements are extracted from the soil as soluble ions by the roots and transported throughout the plant in the xylem.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Most of the elements required for plant nutrition come from the chemical breakdown of soil minerals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Sucrose produced by photosynthesis is transported from the leaves to other parts of the plant in the phloem and plant hormones are transported by a variety of processes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Plants are not passive, but respond to external signals such as light, touch, and injury by moving or growing towards or away from the stimulus, as appropriate.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Tangible evidence of touch sensitivity is the almost instantaneous collapse of leaflets of *Mimosa pudica*, the insect traps of Venus flytrap and bladderworts, and the pollinia of orchids.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The hypothesis that plant growth and development is coordinated by plant hormones or plant growth regulators first emerged in the late 19th century.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Darwin experimented on the movements of plant shoots and roots towards light and gravity, and concluded "It is hardly an exaggeration to say that the tip of the radicle . . acts like the brain of one of the lower animals . . directing the several movements".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] About the same time, the role of auxins (from the Greek *auxein*, to grow) in control of plant growth was first outlined by the Dutch scientist Frits Went.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The first known auxin, indole-3-acetic acid (IAA), which promotes cell growth, was only isolated from plants about 50 years later.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] This compound mediates the tropic responses of shoots and roots towards light and gravity.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Cytokinins are a class of plant hormones named for their control of cell division (especially cytokinesis).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The natural cytokinin zeatin was discovered in corn, *Zea mays*, and is a derivative of the purine adenine.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Zeatin is produced in roots and transported to shoots in the xylem where it promotes cell division, bud development, and the greening of chloroplasts.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The gibberelins, such as gibberelic acid are diterpenes synthesised from acetyl CoA via the mevalonate pathway.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] They are involved in the promotion of germination and dormancy-breaking in seeds, in regulation of plant height by controlling stem elongation and the control of flowering.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Abscisic acid (ABA) occurs in all land plants except liverworts, and is synthesised from carotenoids in the chloroplasts and other plastids.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] It inhibits cell division, promotes seed maturation, and dormancy, and promotes stomatal closure.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] It was so named because it was originally thought to control abscission.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Ethylene is a gaseous hormone that is produced in all higher plant tissues from methionine.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] It is now known to be the hormone that stimulates or regulates fruit ripening and abscission, and it, or the synthetic growth regulator ethephon which is rapidly metabolised to produce ethylene, are used on industrial scale to promote ripening of cotton, pineapples and other climacteric crops.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Another class of phytohormones is the jasmonates, first isolated from the oil of *Jasminum grandiflorum* which regulates wound responses in plants by unblocking the expression of genes required in the systemic acquired resistance response to pathogen attack.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In addition to being the primary energy source for plants, light functions as a signalling device, providing information to the plant, such as how much sunlight the plant receives each day.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] This can result in adaptive changes in a process known as photomorphogenesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Phytochromes are the photoreceptors in a plant that are sensitive to light.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Plant anatomy is the study of the structure of plant cells and tissues, whereas plant morphology is the study of their external form.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] All plants are multicellular eukaryotes, their DNA stored in nuclei.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Other plastids contain storage products such as starch (amyloplasts) or lipids (elaioplasts).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Uniquely, streptophyte cells and those of the green algal order Trentepohliales divide by construction of a phragmoplast as a template for building a cell plate late in cell division.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] , the most common type of plant (three-fifths of all plant species).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] However, no plant actually looks exactly like this.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The bodies of vascular plants including clubmosses, ferns and seed plants (gymnosperms and angiosperms) generally have aerial and subterranean subsystems.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The shoots consist of stems bearing green photosynthesising leaves and reproductive structures.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The underground vascularised roots bear root hairs at their tips and generally lack chlorophyll.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Non-vascular plants, the liverworts, hornworts and mosses do not produce ground-penetrating vascular roots and most of the plant participates in photosynthesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The sporophyte generation is nonphotosynthetic in liverworts but may be able to contribute part of its energy needs by photosynthesis in mosses and hornworts.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The root system and the shoot system are interdependent – the usually nonphotosynthetic root system depends on the shoot system for food, and the usually photosynthetic shoot system depends on water and minerals from the root system.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Cells in each system are capable of creating cells of the other and producing adventitious shoots or roots.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Stolons and tubers are examples of shoots that can grow roots.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Roots that spread out close to the surface, such as those of willows, can produce shoots and ultimately new plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In the event that one of the systems is lost, the other can often regrow it.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In fact it is possible to grow an entire plant from a single leaf, as is the case with plants in *Streptocarpus* sect.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] *Saintpaulia*, or even a single cell – which can dedifferentiate into a callus (a mass of unspecialised cells) that can grow into a new plant.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In vascular plants, the xylem and phloem are the conductive tissues that transport resources between shoots and roots.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Roots are often adapted to store food such as sugars or starch, as in sugar beets and carrots.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Stems mainly provide support to the leaves and reproductive structures, but can store water in succulent plants such as cacti, food as in potato tubers, or reproduce vegetatively as in the stolons of strawberry plants or in the process of layering.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Leaves gather sunlight and carry out photosynthesis.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Large, flat, flexible, green leaves are called foliage leaves.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Gymnosperms, such as conifers, cycads, *Ginkgo*, and gnetophytes are seed-producing plants with open seeds.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Angiosperms are seed-producing plants that produce flowers and have enclosed seeds.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Woody plants, such as azaleas and oaks, undergo a secondary growth phase resulting in two additional types of tissues: wood (secondary xylem) and bark (secondary phloem and cork).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] All gymnosperms and many angiosperms are woody plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Some plants reproduce sexually, some asexually, and some via both means.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Although reference to major morphological categories such as root, stem, leaf, and trichome are useful, one has to keep in mind that these categories are linked through intermediate forms so that a continuum between the categories results.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Furthermore, structures can be seen as processes, that is, process combinations.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Systematic botany is part of systematic biology, which is concerned with the range and diversity of organisms and their relationships, particularly as determined by their evolutionary history.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] It involves, or is related to, biological classification, scientific taxonomy and phylogenetics.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Biological classification is the method by which botanists group organisms into categories such as genera or species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Biological classification is a form of scientific taxonomy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Modern taxonomy is rooted in the work of Carl Linnaeus, who grouped species according to shared physical characteristics.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] These groupings have since been revised to align better with the Darwinian principle of common descent – grouping organisms by ancestry rather than superficial characteristics.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] While scientists do not always agree on how to classify organisms, molecular phylogenetics, which uses DNA sequences as data, has driven many recent revisions along evolutionary lines and is likely to continue to do so.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The dominant classification system is called Linnaean taxonomy.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] It includes ranks and binomial nomenclature.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The nomenclature of botanical organisms is codified in the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (ICN) and administered by the International Botanical Congress.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Kingdom Plantae belongs to Domain Eukaryota and is broken down recursively until each species is separately classified.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The order is: Kingdom; Phylum (or Division); Class; Order; Family; Genus (plural *genera*); Species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The scientific name of a plant represents its genus and its species within the genus, resulting in a single worldwide name for each organism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] For example, the tiger lily is *Lilium columbianum*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] *Lilium* is the genus, and *columbianum* the specific epithet.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The combination is the name of the species.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] When writing the scientific name of an organism, it is proper to capitalise the first letter in the genus and put all of the specific epithet in lowercase.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Additionally, the entire term is ordinarily italicised (or underlined when italics are not available).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The evolutionary relationships and heredity of a group of organisms is called its phylogeny.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Phylogenetic studies attempt to discover phylogenies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The basic approach is to use similarities based on shared inheritance to determine relationships.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] As an example, species of *Pereskia* are trees or bushes with prominent leaves.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] They do not obviously resemble a typical leafless cactus such as an *Echinocactus*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] However, both *Pereskia* and *Echinocactus* have spines produced from areoles (highly specialised pad-like structures) suggesting that the two genera are indeed related.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Judging relationships based on shared characters requires care, since plants may resemble one another through convergent evolution in which characters have arisen independently.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Some euphorbias have leafless, rounded bodies adapted to water conservation similar to those of globular cacti, but characters such as the structure of their flowers make it clear that the two groups are not closely related.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Only derived characters, such as the spine-producing areoles of cacti, provide evidence for descent from a common ancestor.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The results of cladistic analyses are expressed as cladograms: tree-like diagrams showing the pattern of evolutionary branching and descent.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] From the 1990s onwards, the predominant approach to constructing phylogenies for living plants has been molecular phylogenetics, which uses molecular characters, particularly DNA sequences, rather than morphological characters like the presence or absence of spines and areoles.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] The difference is that the genetic code itself is used to decide evolutionary relationships, instead of being used indirectly via the characters it gives rise to.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Clive Stace describes this as having "direct access to the genetic basis of evolution." As a simple example, prior to the use of genetic evidence, fungi were thought either to be plants or to be more closely related to plants than animals.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Genetic evidence suggests that the true evolutionary relationship of multicelled organisms is as shown in the cladogram below – fungi are more closely related to animals than to plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] In 1998, the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group published a phylogeny for flowering plants based on an analysis of DNA sequences from most families of flowering plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] As a result of this work, many questions, such as which families represent the earliest branches of angiosperms, have now been answered.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Investigating how plant species are related to each other allows botanists to better understand the process of evolution in plants.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Despite the study of model plants and increasing use of DNA evidence, there is ongoing work and discussion among taxonomists about how best to classify plants into various taxa.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] Technological developments such as computers and electron microscopes have greatly increased the level of detail studied and speed at which data can be analysed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/botanist-p02] A few symbols are in current use in botany.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/d-appleton-and-company] Appleton & Company merged with The Century Company.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Eponymous halls at both Berkeley and Hopkins pay tribute to his service.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] He was also co-founder of the Russell Trust Association, which administers the business affairs of Yale's Skull and Bones society.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Coit Gilman graduated from Yale College in 1852 with a degree in geography.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] At Yale, he was a classmate of Andrew Dickson White, who would later serve as first president of Cornell University.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] The two were members of the Skull and Bones secret society, and traveled to Europe together after graduation and remained lifelong friends.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman was also a member of the Alpha Delta Phi fraternity.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman would later co-found the Russell Trust Association, the foundation behind Skull and Bones.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] After serving as attaché of the United States legation at St.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Petersburg, Russia from 1853 to 1855, he returned to Yale and was active in planning and raising funds for the founding of Sheffield Scientific School.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman contemplated going into the ministry, and even obtained a license to preach, but later settled on a career in education.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1856 to 1865, Gilman served as librarian of Yale College, and was also concerned with improving the New Haven public school system.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] When the Civil War broke out, Gilman became the recruiting sergeant for the Norton Cadets, a group of Yale graduates and faculty who drilled on the New Haven Green under the oversight of Yale professor William Augustus Norton.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1863, he was appointed professor of geography at the Sheffield Scientific School, and became secretary and librarian as well in 1866.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Having been passed over for the presidency of Yale, for which post Gilman was said to have been the favorite of the younger faculty, he resigned these posts in 1872 to become the third president of the newly organized University of California, Berkeley.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] His work there was hampered by the state legislature, and in 1875 Gilman accepted the offer to establish and become first president of Johns Hopkins University.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Before being formally installed as president in 1876, he spent a year studying university organization and selecting an outstanding staff of teachers and scholars.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] His formal inauguration, on 22 February 1876, has become Hopkins' Commemoration Day, the day on which many university presidents have chosen to be installed in office.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Among the legendary educators he assembled to teach at Johns Hopkins were classicist Basil Lanneau Gildersleeve, mathematician James Joseph Sylvester, historian Herbert Baxter Adams and chemist Ira Remsen.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1876, Gilman was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman's primary interest was in fostering advanced instruction and research, and as president he developed the first American graduate university in the German tradition.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1884, Gilman was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman was also active in founding Johns Hopkins Hospital in 1889 and Johns Hopkins Medical School in 1893.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] He founded and was for many years president of the Charity Organization of Baltimore, and in 1897 he served on the commission to draft a new charter for Baltimore.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1896 to 1897, he was a member of the commission to settle the boundary line between Venezuela and British Guiana.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman served as a trustee of the John F.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Slater and Peabody education funds and as a member of John D.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] In this capacity, he became active in the promotion of education in the southern United States.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] He was president of the National Civil Service Reform League (1901–1907) and the American Oriental Society (1893–1906), vice president of the Archaeological Institute of America, and executive officer of the Maryland Geological Survey.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] He retired from Johns Hopkins in 1901, but accepted the presidency (1902–1904) of the newly founded Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] His books include biographies of James Monroe (1883) and James Dwight Dana, a collection of addresses entitled *University Problems* (1898), and *The Launching of a University* (1906).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1902 he served (jointly with Harry Thurston Peck and Frank Moore Colby) as editor of *The New International Encyclopedia*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] His first wife was Mary Van Winker Ketcham, daughter of Tredwell Ketcham of New York City.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] They married on December 4, 1861, and had two daughters: Alice, who married Everett Wheeler; and Elisabeth Gilman, who became a social activist and was a candidate for mayor of Baltimore, and for governor and senator of Maryland, on the Socialist Party of America ticket.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Mary Ketcham Gilman died in 1869, and Daniel Coit Gilman married his second wife, Elizabeth Dwight Woolsey, daughter of John M.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Woolsey of Cleveland, and niece of Yale president Theodore Dwight Woolsey, in 1877.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Gilman's brother Edward Whiting Gilman was married to Julia Silliman, daughter of Yale University professor and chemist Benjamin Silliman.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Coit Gilman died in Norwich, Connecticut.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] The original academic building on the Homewood campus of the Johns Hopkins University, Gilman Hall, is named in his honor.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1897, he helped found a preparatory school called 'The Country School for Boys' on the Johns Hopkins campus.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Upon relocation in 1910, it was renamed in his honor and today, the Gilman School continues to be regarded among the nation's elite private boys' schools.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] On the University of California, Berkeley campus, Gilman Hall, also named in his honor, is the oldest building of the College of Chemistry and a National Historic Chemical Landmark.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Named for Gilman as well is Gilman Street in Berkeley.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman Drive, which passes through the University of California, San Diego campus in La Jolla, CA is also named for Gilman.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] The Daniel Coit Gilman Summer House, in Maine, was declared a U.S.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman High School in Northeast Harbor, Maine, was named for Daniel Coit Gilman, who was active in local educational affairs, but it was later rebuilt and christened Mount Desert High School.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] He was awarded American Library Association Honorary Membership in 1895.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] The Papers of Daniel Coit Gilman were donated to Johns Hopkins University by Gilman's daughter Elisabeth, and are open on an unrestricted basis to the public at the Milton S.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Aside from many photographs of Gilman and his contemporaries, the papers include Gilman's correspondence with leading figures of the day, including Charles W.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/daniel-coit-gilman] Du Bois, Booker T Washington and others.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The ***Dictionary of American Biography*** (**DAB**) was a multi-volume dictionary published in New York City by Charles Scribner's Sons under the auspices of the American Council of Learned Societies (ACLS).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The dictionary was first proposed to the Council in 1920 by historian Frederick Jackson Turner.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The first edition was published in 20 volumes from 1928 to 1936, appearing at a rate of two or three volumes per year.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] These 20 volumes contained 15,000 biographies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] In 1946, the 20 volumes were released as a ten-volume set, with each of the ten volumes divided into two parts (Part 1 and Part 2) corresponding to two volumes of the first edition combined into one, the page numbering of the first edition being retained.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The ACLS appealed to Adolph Ochs, publisher of *The New York Times*, for funding.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] He loaned the Council $50,000 per year for 10 years.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The dictionary included no biographies of the living, and some period of residence in the United States was required for inclusion.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] These twenty volumes had numerous quirks.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] For example, the entry for Mary Baker Eddy filled eight pages, the entry for Mark Twain only six and a half.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Connecticut and Massachusetts were overrepresented, while Arizona had just one entry.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Noticeable omissions included, among others, Sojourner Truth, Martha Washington, Scott Joplin, Charles Guiteau, and Joe Hill.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] In the early volumes terms such as "red men" and "savages" were occasionally used.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] With the passage of time the usefulness of the series as a reference work waned.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Ten supplementary volumes were issued, between 1944 and 1995, each covering people who had died after the previous supplement.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The first eight supplements were produced under the auspices of the American Council of Learned Societies.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] By terms of an agreement signed in 1990, Macmillan was allowed to produce the final two supplements, covering people who had died through 1980, without the council's participation.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] (Macmillan acquired the dictionary's publisher Charles Scribner's Sons in 1984.) When Macmillan in 1993 applied to the ACLS for permission to publish a further supplement, the Council refused.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] In mid 1995 Macmillan announced that it would put the old D.A.B. on CD-ROM, with updates to the existing entries as well as new biographies of people left out of the old dictionary.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Katz, then president of the council, protested that the publisher had no legal right to do so without the council's approval.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] "Our client has taken the position that we want the original work preserved in its pristine form," said Lawrence S.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Robbins, a lawyer representing the council.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] "We regard it as a treasure and we don't want it to be tinkered with.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The suit says, in part, we don't want it updated, missing-personed, digitized, colorized.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] We want it to exist the way it is." Macmillan moved to have the lawsuit thrown out.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] The ACLS signed a contract with Oxford University Press to publish a new series to be called the *American National Biography*, with financial support from the National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Macmillan, which had acquired Scribner's, decided to publish its own project supplementing the original *Dictionary of American Biography*, and called it *The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives* (SEAL), with Kenneth T.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/dictionary-of-american-biography] Jackson (who had been editor-in-chief of the DAB from 1990 to 1996) as the editor-in-chief.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] The neologism ***Mountweazel*** was coined by *The New Yorker* writer Henry Alford in an article that mentioned a fictitious biographical entry intentionally placed as a copyright trap in the 1975 *New Columbia Encyclopedia*.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] The entry described Lillian Virginia Mountweazel as a fountain designer turned photographer, who died in an explosion while on assignment for *Combustibles* magazine.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Allegedly, she was widely known for her photo-essays of unusual subject matter, including New York City buses, the cemeteries of Paris, and rural American mailboxes.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] According to the encyclopedia's editor, it is a tradition for encyclopedias to put a fake entry to trap competitors for plagiarism.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] The surname came to be associated with all such fictitious entries.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] The term *nihilartikel*, combining the Latin *nihil* ("nothing") and German *Artikel* ("article"), is sometimes used.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] By including a trivial piece of false information in a larger work, it is easier to demonstrate subsequent plagiarism if the fictitious entry is copied along with other material.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] An admission of this motive appears in the preface to Chambers' 1964 mathematical tables: "those [errors] that are known to exist form an uncomfortable trap for any would-be plagiarist".
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Similarly, trap streets may be included in a map, or invented phone numbers in a telephone directory.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Fictitious entries may be used to demonstrate copying, but to prove legal infringement, the material must also be shown to be eligible for copyright (see *Feist v.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Rural*, Fred Worth lawsuit or *Nester's Map & Guide Corp. v.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Fictitious entries on maps may be called phantom settlements, trap streets, paper towns, cartographer's follies, or other names.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] They are intended to help reveal copyright infringements.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] They are not to be confused with paper streets, which are streets which are planned but as of the printing of the map have not yet been built.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Some publications such as those published by Harvard biologist John Bohannon are used to detect lack of academic scrutiny, editorial oversight, fraud, or data dredging on the part of authors or their publishers.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Trap publications may be used by publishers to immediately reject articles citing them, or by academics to detect journals of ill repute (those that would publish them or works citing them).
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] A survey of food tastes by the US Army in the 1970s included "funistrada", "buttered ermal", and "braised trake" to control for inattentive answers.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] In 1985, the fictitious town of Ripton, Massachusetts, was "created" in an effort to protest the ignorance of state officials about rural areas.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] The town received a budget appropriation and several grants before the hoax was revealed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Fictitious entries may be used to demonstrate copying, but to prove legal infringement, the material must also be shown to be eligible for copyright.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] However, due to the decision in *Feist v.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Rural* that "information alone without a minimum of original creativity cannot be protected by copyright", there are very few cases in which copyright has been proven, and many are dismissed.
[src:appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography/fictitious-entry] Often there will be errors in maps, dictionaries, and other publications, that are not deliberate and thus are not fictitious entries.
